@node "INSTALL" "SN RTFRI v1.0 - Installation Procedures"
@toc "MAIN"
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
  SN RTFRI v1.0 - Installation Procedures
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘

 1  Run the included installation script either of the following
    two ways:

    a.  Type "Installer Install_RTFRI" from the Shell.

    b.  Click on the "Install_RTFRI" icon from Workbench.

 2  The installation script moves the required files to your specified
    location and creates an environment variable pointing to that location.

 3  Customizing RTFRI's configuration file (_RTFRI.cfg):

    a.  With your favorite editor, load up the example config file.

    b.  Modify the configuration to suit your needs, adding or removing
        programs as required.

        Here are the special drop-ins that RTFRI understands:

        %c  = # of columns    %f  = Path/filename passed to RTFRI
        %l  = # of lines      %p  = CNet port called from
        %r  = Remote usable

 4  Add the calls to your bbsmenu file, using your favorite editor.
    I've added them to "1; Maintenance," but they could be placed
    elsewhere if you want others without maint access to be able to
    use them.  Here is what I added to mine when used with the example
    config file:

    MT  |{#4SN:SN_RTFRI %23 1}
    CED |{#4SN:SN_RTFRI %23 2}
    MTV |{#4SN:SN_RTFRI %23 3}
    MOST|{#4SN:SN_RTFRI %23 4}
    VIS |{#4SN:SN_RTFRI %23 5}

    Note that the above { is actually a control-Q command.

    Your path may be different, but the first variable "%23" MUST be
    included.  It is required for RTFRI to talk to CNet's port.  The
    second variable is also required, but depends on which line of the
    config file it points to.

    For example, MT above points to line 1 of the config file, which
    looks like this:

    MoreText LINES=%l COLUMNS=%c ALTCURSOR NOFILELINKS %f %r

 5  Reload your bbstext/bbsmenu via CNet's Control Panel menu (option
    #3, "Text/menu reload  RAmiga-T" and you're all set!

 6  If ReqTools is available and no arguments are specified on CNet's
    command line, a requester will pop-up on CNet's screen and ask for
    a file.  If RT isn't, it simply asks for the filename itself.

    Also, even if RT IS available, it will NOT be used if the caller is
    remote, for obvious reasons.  :)

 7  Examples (all using my config)

    Situation:  (calling remote or local & RT not-available)

    CNet> MT                     Asks for a filename before calling MT.
    CNet> MT t:                  Same as above.
    CNet> MT t:dsds              If exists, calls MT with that file,
                                 otherwise asks for a filename.

    Situation:  (local, RT available)

    CNet> MT                     Pops up requester defaulting to the users'
                                 mail dir asking for a file before calling MT.
    CNet> MT t:                  Same as above, except defaulting to t:.
    CNet> MT t:dsds              If exists, calls MT with that file,
                                 otherwise pops up a requester defaulting
                                 to t:.

    If MT didn't allow remote usage, RTFRI will let you know.

    If the specified drive/volumn doesn't exist or an assignment is not
    made, it will abort.  No requesters are ever popped up unless RTFRI
    is damn sure someone is there to handle them.  :)

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@endnode
